# Frequently Asked String Interview Programs

### Check Palindrome

```java
String str = "madam";

String rev = new StringBuilder(str).reverse().toString();

if(str.equals(rev))
    System.out.println("Palindrome");
else
    System.out.println("Not Palindrome");
```

### Count Vowels

```java
String str = "Java Programming";
int count = 0;

for(char ch : str.toLowerCase().toCharArray()) {
    if("aeiou".indexOf(ch) != -1)
        count++;
}

System.out.println(count);
```

### Count Words

```java
String str = "Java is easy";

String[] words = str.split(" ");

System.out.println(words.length);
```

Output:

```
3
```

## Summary of Important String Methods

| Method          | Purpose              |
| --------------- | -------------------- |
| `length()`      | Length of string     |
| `charAt()`      | Get character        |
| `substring()`   | Extract part         |
| `equals()`      | Compare strings      |
| `contains()`    | Check text exists    |
| `replace()`     | Replace text         |
| `trim()`        | Remove spaces        |
| `toUpperCase()` | Convert to uppercase |
| `toLowerCase()` | Convert to lowercase |
| `indexOf()`     | Find position        |
| `split()`       | Split into parts     |
| `isEmpty()`     | Check empty string   |

These are the most commonly used String methods in Java interviews, exams, and real-world programming.
